@flexiarg corps/working-where-others-can-see
@title Working Where Others Can See (Individual Contributor → Collaborative Team Member)
@audience CORPS mentors, doctoral supervisors, research stewards
@tone analytic
@style design-pattern
@sigils [👀/示]

! conclusion: Working Where Others Can See

  + context: You are shifting an individual workflow into a collaborative team setting where visibility matters.

  + if: A project depends on mutual visibility of tasks, decisions, and intermediate outputs, yet the researcher’s workflow remains private or idiosyncratic.

  + however: Teams cannot coordinate or intervene early when work stays on personal drives or in opaque notebooks.

  + then: Move key elements of the workflow into shared spaces—open notes, reproducible scripts, transparent task boards—and annotate decision points so colleagues can interpret and respond without extra meetings.

  + because: Collaboration relies on visible work surfaces. When intermediate steps are reviewable, teams reduce duplication, coordinate effectively, and offer support before issues harden into blockers.

  + next-steps:
+   next[Choose one shared workspace (notes, repo, or task board) and migrate the next deliverable there.]
+   next[Add a brief decision log so teammates can respond asynchronously.]
